title: Excitation Functions of High-Energy Alpha-Particle Induced Nuclear Reactions on Aluminium and Magnesium- Production of Mg-28.

x4freetext: Excitation Functions of High-Energy Alpha-Particle
Induced Nuclear Reactions on Aluminium and Magnesium-
Production of Mg-28.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Applied Radiation and Isotopes, Vol.27, p.431 (1976)

x4freetext: The Incident Alpha-Particle Energies were 156 or 97
MeV. The Beam Currents Varied Between 50 and 520
Nanoamperes.Irradiation Times were 15 Min For
Short-Lived Reaction Products and Between 3.5 and
19 Hours For Studies on Longer-Lived Nuclides. The
Used Target Stacks Consisted of Up to 52 Single Foils.
The Energy Degradation of the Alpha-Particles was
Calculated According to C.F.Williamson Et Al. Report
Cea-R-3042(1966).The Beam Current was Determined by
2 Independent Methods. In Addition to Using the
Formation of Na-24 As Monitor (SEE SUBENTRY B0174002),
The Na-24 Activity Produced in the First Al-Foil of
The Stack was Compared to That Produced in a Separately
Irradiated Thin Al-Foil, For Which the Total Charge
Was Measured with a Faraday Cup.
1.For a Few Values Typical Error Bars are Given. In the
Energy Errors Uncertainties in the Alpha Energies Due
To Energy and Angular Straggling, and Errors in the
Thicknesses of Target Foils and in the Range - Energy
Relationship are Included. The Uncertainty in Energy
Amounted to 1-3 MeV, Dependent on the Energy Region
And Target Thickness.
2.Total Errors were Obtained Summing Up All
Individual Errors in Quadrature:
Foil Thicknesses (2%),
Beam Current Measurement (<5%),
Detector Efficiency (4%),
Counting Statistics and Photopeak Integration.
A Comparitive Study of the Al-27(ALPHA,3P)Mg-28 and
Mg-26(ALPHA,2P)Mg-28 Reactions For the Production of
Mg-28 is Made.
Nekw
Some Corrections have Been Included by
CAJAD
Last checking has been done.
After Measuring the Relative Excitation Function Up
To 156 MeV, the Data were Normalized to the Values
Of Martens and Schweimer (SEE MONIT-REF) In the
Overlapping Energy Region of 75-103 MeV.
Aluminium Foils, Thicknesses Ranging Between 50 and 500
Micrometer. The Purity of Aluminum was Greater Than
99.99%. The Thicknesses of the Foils were Determined
By Weighing.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Zeitschrift fuer Physik, Vol.233, p.170 (1970)

x4freetext: The Yield was Calculated Using the Measured Excitation
Function.
A Contribution from the Reaction Al-27(N,ALPHA)Na-24
Must be Considered Only at Projectile Energies Below
About 50 MeV.
It is Pointed Out by the Authors That the Given Curve
Describes the Total Formation of Na-24, Including That,
Formed Via the Al-27(ALPHA,BE-7)Na-24 Reaction, and
Some Contribution from the Al-27(N,ALPHA) Reaction
Below 50 MeV.

x4freetext: The Yield was Calculated Using the Measured Excitation
Function.
Mg-28 is Formed in a Carrier-Free State.
Major Radionuclidic Impurities Associated with the
Production of Mg-28 are be-7 (BO174004), Na-22
Since the Ratios of Mg-28 Yield to Yields of these
Impurities is Nearly Independent of the Projectile
Energy, the Authors Conclude That For Radiomedical
Purposes a Chemical Separation of Mg is Absolutely
Essential.

Highest Incident Energies Up to 20%.
See Subent B0174001  Err-Analys  Item 1.
A Thick Target Yield For Mg-28 is Calculated
From the Excitation Function.  A Value of 155
Microcurie Per Microampere*Hour is Quoted For an
Alpha-Particles Energy of 140 MeV For a 100% Enriched
Mg-26 Target.
The Authors Point Out a Distict Difference in Shape
Of the Excitation Functions of (A,2P)- Reactions
On Mg-26 and on Al-27 (SEE SUBENTRY B0174007).
Major Radionuclidic Impurities Associated with the
Production of Mg-28 are be-7 (B0174004), Na-22
Since the Ratios of Mg-28 Yield to Yields of
These Impurities is Nearly Independent of the
Projectile Energy, the Authors Conclude That For
Radiomedical Purposes a Chemical Separation of Mg
Is Absolutely Essential.
